{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535642"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:58:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:58:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15492"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15492"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0.38,0.14,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103244"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8183"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15492"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85662"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"302"},{"type":"tags","id":"623"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"4034"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36580"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103244"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of worsening cough and breathlessness. She has metastatic lung cancer and is receiving immunotherapy. Her medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and osteoarthritis. Her medications include pembrolizumab, metformin, amlodipine, and paracetamol. She lives at home with her partner and is fully independent with activities of daily living.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. She is oriented. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. There are coarse crepitations in both lung bases. Investigations reveal white cell count 18.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0) and C-reactive protein 220 mg/L (\u0026lt;5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has recently completed an advance care directive which states she does not want cardiopulmonary resuscitation, intubation, or intravenous antibiotics and wishes for a palliative approach to any life limiting illness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange intensive care review","Commence short term intravenous antibiotics","Discuss goals of care with patient","Arrange palliative care review","Follow her advance care directive and begin comfort based care"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of sepsis (tachycardia, hypotension, tachypnoea, fever, raised inflammatory markers) in the context of metastatic lung cancer and a recent advance care directive declining certain interventions. While advance care directives are important legal documents that should generally be followed, they only come into effect when a person loses decision-making capacity. This patient appears to still have capacity to participate in decisions about her care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscussing goals of care\u003C/strong\u003E with the patient is the most appropriate first step. This allows confirmation of her wishes in the current context, explores her understanding of the situation, and helps establish what interventions would align with her values and preferences. The discussion should include her prognosis, the reversibility of the current deterioration, and available treatment options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing intravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would directly contradict her advance care directive without first confirming her current wishes. While antibiotics might treat the likely pneumonia, proceeding without discussion would not respect her autonomy. Some patients may accept short-term interventions for potentially reversible conditions while still declining more invasive treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging intensive care review\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate given her documented wishes against intubation and her advanced cancer diagnosis. This would likely lead to unnecessary distress and consultations, particularly given her clear documentation regarding not wanting invasive interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollowing her advance care directive and beginning comfort based care\u003C/strong\u003E without discussion is premature. The directive only comes into effect when she loses decision-making capacity, which does not appear to be the case here. Immediate implementation without exploring her current wishes could miss an opportunity to treat a potentially reversible condition if that aligns with her current preferences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging palliative care review\u003C/strong\u003E, while likely to be appropriate at some point, is not the most immediate priority. The first step should be clarifying goals of care with the patient and partner, after which palliative care involvement can be arranged as part of a considered management plan.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Advance care directives come into effect when a person loses decision-making capacity, not automatically when they become unwell.","Goals of care discussions are essential when managing acute deterioration in patients with advanced cancer.","Palliative care involvement should be considered early in patients with advanced cancer experiencing acute deterioration."],"references":["Australian Commission on Safety and Quality in Health Care. National Consensus Statement: Essential elements for safe and high\u2011quality end\u2011of\u2011life care. Sydney: ACSQHC; 2023. Available online at ; https://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/sites/default/files/2023-12/national_consensus_statement_-_essential_elements_for_safe_and_high-quality_end-of-life_care.pdf","Hickman SE, Lum HD, Walling AM, Savoy A, Sudore RL. The care planning umbrella: The evolution of advance care planning. Journal of the American Geriatrics Society. 2023 Jul;71(7):2350. Available online at ; https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10958534/","Australian Commission on Safety and Quality in Health Care. Sepsis Clinical Care Standard. Sydney: ACSQHC; 2022. Available online at ; https://www.safetyandquality.gov.au/sites/default/files/2022-06/sepsis_clinical_care_standard_2022.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85662"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15492"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85662"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T21:02:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T20:21:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8183"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103244"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"